opment, gender and child-related issues for the past fifteen years. Her edited volume titled Concerns, Conflicts and Cohesions: Universalization of Elementary Education in India was published by Oxford University Press, New Delhi, in 2009. She is an associate editor of both the Indian Journal of Human Development and the Indian Journal of Labour Economics. E-mail: preet.rustagi@ihdindia.com Rajini Menon, an independent consultant, is working on areas related to gender, education and health. She has a Ph.D in Economics from Calicut University, Kerala. She is associated with the Institute for Human Development, Delhi, and is also one of the course writers to School of Gender Studies, IGNOU, Delhi. E-mail: menon.rajini@gmail.com Comments or clarifications can be addressed by email to the authors. 2 Abstract Women\u2019s command over assets is highlighted as a key element for gender equity and empowerment. This paper explores the gender dimensions of asset ownership. It examines the multitude of inheritance systems and legal provisions existing in the Asia-Pacific region with special reference to the challenges faced by women. The efforts taken throughout the region to ensure equitable rights for women over land, property and resources have also been studied. The paper concludes with policy recommendations for ensuring gender equitable rights over assets. The authors underscore the need for building up empirical information and statistical data on individual ownership of assets to enable evidence-based advocacy for requisite policy changes. Key words: asset ownership, human development, gender inequalities The views expressed in this publication are those of the author(s) and do not necessarily represent those of the United Nations, including UNDP, or the UN Member States. This paper was commissioned by the Human Development Report Unit as a technical background paper to inform the Asia-Pacific Human Development Report, \u201cPower, Voice and Rights\u201d. The data may differ from that finally presented in Asia-Pacific Human Development Report. Readers may contact the author directly for any clarifications, queries on data, inferences, and conclusions or to engage in discussion. This paper has not been copyedited. 3 CONTENTS List of Figures and Tables List of Boxes Abbreviations 1. INTRODUCTION AND CONTEXT 1.1 Arguments for Women\u2019s Independent Rights to Assets 1.1.1 Defining Assets 1.1.2 Arguments for Women\u2019s Command over Assets 1.1.3 Rationale for Closing Gender Asset Gaps 1.2 Socio-economic Status of Women in Asia-Pacific Region 2. EVIDENCE ON GENDER ASSET GAPS 2.1 Command over Major Assets (Land, Property and Housing) 2.1.1 South and West Asia 2.1.2 North East Asia 2.1.3 South East Asia 2.1.4 The Pacific Region 3. APPROACHES TO IMPROVE WOMEN\u2019S COMMAND OVER ECONOMIC AND FINANCIAL RESOURCES 3.1 Women\u2019s Entrepreneurship 3.1.1 Micro-enterprises by Women 3.2 Microfinance 3.2.1Women\u2019s Access to Microfinance\u2014Experiences from Countries 4.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "64b4a299-6f3d-420c-b28f-c162b01a6781": {"__data__": {"id_": "64b4a299-6f3d-420c-b28f-c162b01a6781", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/aphdr-technical-background-paper-2010/10", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "APHDR Technical Background Paper 2010/10", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/aphdr-technical-background-paper-2010/10", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "601da56afae01de7be5a896735ec3